The Marquis de Prie, Ambaador from the Queen of Hungary to the Cantons of Switzerland, has preſented a Memorial to the Helvetic Body, in which he ſugges, that their granting Troops to the King of Spain is a dire Violation of their Neutrality ; and his Excellency abſo‑ lutely inﬁs on their refung a Paage to the Spaniards through their Territories.
All the Advices from Holland agree, that the Aurians gain Ground every Day in the Upper Palatinate ; and that the Mortality among the French in Bavaria continued to a very terrible Degree.
Private Letters by the la French Mail inform us, that a great Number of the Oﬃcers of the Army are already ſet out to join their reſpeive Corps, and others are pre‑ paring to follow.

We hear that the Principal Oﬃcers of his Majey's Ordnance have lately purchaſed from the Dutch a large Train of Artillery, and other Habiliments of War which are deined for the Attance of the Queen of Hungary.

Yeerday ſe'nnight, at Six in the Evening, the Poll for the Eleion of a Member for St. Alban's cloſed, when the Numbers were, for Mr. Stanley 325 and Mr. Grimon 303, whereupon the former was declared duly eleed, and on Monday took his Seat in the Houſe of Commons.

They write from Wootton‐Baet in Wiltſhire, that on Sunday, the 30th of January, about Eleven in the Forenoon, a Fire broke out at the Houſe of Mr. Stephen Pearſe, a Wheelwright near the Church, which grea�y alarm'd the Congregation, and the whole Town, and in an Hour and Half's Time it deroy'd eighteen Houſes ; and by which Misfortune many People were entirely ruin'd.

Monday Blair and Deacon, the two Perſons convied of Sodomitical Praices at the la Seons at the Old Baily, were brought to the Pillory at Cheapde Conduit, and the latter was put into it ; but Blair appear'd to be ſo extremely ill, that he was laid on the Pillory almo naked, (as brought from Newgate) and was ſo ſeverely pelted, whipp'd and tumbled about by the Populace, that he was carry'd back quite inſenble to the Goal, where he died about Seven o'Clock the ſame Night ; Deacon was alſo treated much in the ſame Manner, but being a rong young Fellow, it is believed he will recover.

As mo People ſuppoſe they cannot be marry'd in Lent without paying double Fees, this is to let them know, that the Fees at the following Chapel are no more in Lent than any other Time.

Some People having alledged that Night Marriages are of pernicious Conſequences to the Publick, Mr. Keith begs Leave to aſk them what ill Conſequence would be pre‑ vented by his not marrying at Night, when People could ill be marry'd at Night in the Fleet ? But he is ready and willing to conﬁne the Marriages to the Day‐time, provided all other Perſons will do the ſame.

That Mr. Keith, the Minier of May‐Fair Chapel, not being under the Authority or Juriſdiion of the Biſhop or his Court, theſe xteen Months pa, looks upon him‑ ſelf to be no ways aﬀeed by any thing they can do‑ And therefore the Marrrage‐Fees, Licence on a Five Shil‑ ling Stamp, together with the Certiﬁcate, amount but to a Guinea on Sundays till Six at Night, except the Time of Divine Service, which is from half an Hour after Eleven till One, and from Four till Five o'Clock ; but on the Week Days it is a Guinea till Four, a Guinea and a half till Seven, and Two Guineas after Seven at Night.
